<h2>The Question</h2>
<p>
  The polyglot panel's live-test slice (<a href="/backlog/912-polyglot-panel-live-test-sandbox-execute-the-generated-wrapp/">#912</a>),
  under the Block Explorer epic (<a href="/backlog/746-block-explorer-interactive-fui-block-workbench/">#746</a>),
  wants to <strong>execute</strong> — not merely show — the per-framework wrapper that
  <code>generateWrapper(cem, target)</code> emits, and render it live with runtime-error surfacing.
  Tracing the real output (<code>fui:tools/gen-wrapper/genWrapper.mjs:119</code>) the React wrapper is
  literally <code>import React … return React.createElement('&lt;fui-tag&gt;', { ref, …attrs }, children)</code>
  — so a live preview needs three things the workbench does <strong>not</strong> have today: in-browser
  TS+JSX transpile, a React/Vue <strong>runtime</strong> reachable from the preview, and the
  <strong>real custom element defined where the wrapper runs</strong>. The workbench registers blocks via
  bundler-resolved dynamic imports (<code>fui:workbench/registry.ts:149</code> —
  <code>import('../blocks/droplist/AutoComplete')</code>), which expose <strong>no stable per-block module
  URL</strong> to re-import elsewhere. This survey grounds
  <a href="/backlog/955-decide-the-polyglot-live-test-sandbox-strategy-framework-run/">#955</a>:
  <strong>what strategy backs the live-test sandbox?</strong>
</p>

<h2>What the survey found</h2>
<p>
  The transpiler choice (esbuild-wasm vs Babel-standalone) is a confirmed <em>impl detail</em>. The two
  real axes are <strong>element isolation</strong> and <strong>framework-runtime source</strong> — and
  the closest analog already answers both.
</p>

