<h3>Load-bearing platform facts (these ground the defaults)</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Import maps are document-scoped and resolve-once.</strong> A fresh <code>&lt;iframe srcdoc&gt;</code>
    gets a fresh import map per preview; a same-document mount cannot re-resolve frameworks across
    previews/targets.</li>
  <li><strong><code>customElements.define</code> throws on re-definition.</strong> A same-document sandbox
    can only reuse the workbench's already-registered element; an iframe gets a clean registry.</li>
  <li><strong>Executed wrapper code is framework code, not host DOM.</strong> A thrown error in a
    same-document run can break the workbench shell; an iframe contains it.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How it reshapes the forks</h2>
<p>
  <strong>Fork A — element isolation.</strong> The Lit Playground precedent (also web-components-first,
  also live-executing) plus bias-toward-separation move the best-end-state default from the item's
  interim <em>A2 (same-document)</em> to <strong>A1 (iframe <code>srcdoc</code> + own import-map)</strong>.
  The genuine counterweight keeping A2 live: A1 must get the element <em>defined inside the frame</em>,
  which needs a stable per-block module URL the registry doesn't expose today — a real build cost in
  #912. But that is build <em>effort</em> (filed to the build, per <em>fork-is-not-a-prioritization-tool</em>),
  not a merit defect, so the fork rules A1 on merit.
</p>
<p>
  <strong>Fork B — framework-runtime source.</strong> The invariant: the runtime must
  <strong>never enter FUI's shipped bundle</strong> (bundling react/vue into <code>@frontierui</code> is
  the flawed, excluded branch — a web-components lib shipping framework runtimes). Among the
  framework-free options the item defaulted to CDN import-map (esm.sh); but the item <em>also</em>
  requires an e2e plan that doesn't depend on external network ("vendor the runtimes or stub"). If
  vendoring must exist for CI anyway, CDN means maintaining <strong>two paths</strong> (CDN dev +
  vendored CI). A single <strong>locally-vendored devDependency served into the sandbox iframe</strong>
  serves dev + CI from one path, stays framework-free (a devDep is not the shipped bundle), and — paired
  with the already-local esbuild-wasm — makes the whole sandbox offline + deterministic.
</p>
<p>
  The two forks are <strong>coupled</strong>: B's framework-free isolation is cleanest when the runtime
  loads <em>inside the iframe</em> (A1), not the workbench document (A2). <strong>A1 + local-vendored</strong>
  is the coherent combined strategy that mirrors Lit Playground (iframe + import-map) while honoring FUI's
  framework-free principle and the offline-CI requirement.
</p>

<h2>Classification</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Layer:</strong> a FUI-owned devtool inside the workbench (<code>fui:workbench/</code>,
    <code>locus: frontierui</code>) — not a WE standard (<em>impl-is-not-a-standard</em>; #809 the
    workbench is FUI-owned). Nothing crosses into <code>@webeverything</code>.</li>
  <li><strong>Protocol vs impl:</strong> no new protocol — it consumes only the already-ratified
    <a href="/protocols/#protocol-custom-elements-manifest">Custom Elements Manifest</a> (#626) the
    wrapper is generated from, plus the #506 verdict / #891 runner for the downstream badge (#913).</li>
  <li><strong>DI seam?</strong> No runtime-DI seam — author/dev-time execution, not a registry the
    running standard consults.</li>
  <li><strong>Most-permissive default:</strong> the transpiler stays swappable impl (esbuild-wasm
    recommended for module resolution); the isolation + runtime-source axes are ruled to best end-state
    above.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Recommendation handed to #955</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Fork A → A1 (iframe <code>srcdoc</code> isolation).</strong> ~70%. Residual: needs a stable
    per-block module URL the registry doesn't expose; the #815 "one document, no channel" workbench
    philosophy is A2's principled counter — flag for the decider's skeptic pass.</li>
  <li><strong>Fork B → local-vendored devDependency served into the sandbox iframe.</strong> ~75%.
    Residual: esm.sh CDN is genuinely less wiring and is what Lit Playground ships. Bundling into FUI
    stays the ruled-out flawed branch either way.</li>
  <li><strong>Supported by default (not forks):</strong> transpiler = esbuild-wasm in a Web Worker;
    console/error surfacing via the Lit-Playground <code>postMessage</code> monkey-patch; the e2e plan
    reuses the same vendored runtime (no external network), resolving the item's e2e ask.</li>
</ul>

